<h2><span class="time">19:00 - 20:30</span> SECTION 8: STREAM — MILESTONE-BASED PAYMENTS</h2>

<div class="action">Navigate to paypol.xyz/stream.</div>

<div class="script">
Now we come to <b>Stream Settlement</b> — one of PayPol's most important features.
<br><br>
Here's the real-world problem: When you hire an AI agent or freelancer for a large project — say $10,000 — you don't want to pay everything upfront. What if they don't deliver? But the worker also doesn't want to finish everything before getting paid — what if the client doesn't pay?
<br><br>
<b>Stream solves this problem</b>. Instead of one lump payment, you split the project into phases called <b>milestones</b>. Each milestone has a specific dollar amount and a clear deliverable. Funds are only released when a milestone is approved.
<br><br>
Here's how it works:
<br>
1. <b>Client creates a Stream</b> — sets the total budget and splits it into milestones (e.g., Phase 1 Wireframe $2,000, Phase 2 Frontend $3,000, Phase 3 Backend $2,500...)
<br>
2. <b>Funds are locked</b> in the <b>StreamV1</b> smart contract on Tempo L1 — nobody can withdraw them
<br>
3. <b>Agent completes</b> a milestone and clicks "Submit Deliverable" — attaching proof (proof hash)
<br>
4. <b>Client reviews</b> and has 2 options: <b>Approve</b> (funds automatically transfer to agent) or <b>Reject</b> (sends it back for revision)
<br>
5. When all milestones are approved — the Stream is complete, 100% of funds have been disbursed
</div>

<div class="action">Point to the 5 stat cards at the top: Total Streams, Active, Completed, Total Volume, Milestones.</div>

<div class="script">
Here you can see the system overview: how many streams exist, how many are active, completed, total value locked, and the milestone approval ratio.
<br><br>
You can also filter by status: ALL, ACTIVE, COMPLETED, CANCELLED.
</div>

<div class="action">Point to the 3 stream cards — explain the card structure.</div>

<div class="script">
Each stream card shows you at a glance: the agent name (e.g., DesignMaster-AI), total budget, days remaining until deadline, and the <b>milestone progress bars</b> at the bottom.
<br><br>
Look at these colored bars — each one represents a milestone:
<br>
— <b>Gray</b> = Pending — not started yet
<br>
— <b>Yellow</b> = Submitted — agent submitted, awaiting review
<br>
— <b>Green</b> = Approved — approved and paid out
<br>
— <b>Red</b> = Rejected — rejected, needs revision
<br><br>
One glance tells you exactly where each project stands.
</div>

<div class="action">Click on the "DesignMaster-AI" stream — show the detail view with milestones.</div>

<div class="script">
Inside is the detailed view. At the top are 4 key metrics: <b>Total Budget</b>, <b>Released</b> (amount paid out), <b>Progress</b> (milestones completed), and <b>Deadline</b> (time remaining).
<br><br>
The purple gradient progress bar shows the ratio of funds released to total budget. It's animated for a clear visual indicator.
<br><br>
Below is the <b>milestone timeline</b> — each milestone displays:
<br>
— The task name (e.g., "Phase 1: Wireframes and UI Mockups")
<br>
— The amount (e.g., 2,000 AlphaUSD)
<br>
— Status with colored icon (Pending, Submitted, Approved, Rejected)
<br>
— Links to transactions on the block explorer (Submit TX, Approve TX)
<br><br>
Everything is on-chain, transparent, and anyone can verify on Tempo Explorer.
</div>

<div class="action">Explain the Approve/Reject flow — point to the action buttons.</div>

<div class="script">
When an agent submits a milestone, the client sees an <b>Approve &amp; Release</b> button and a <b>Reject</b> button.
<br><br>
— Click Approve: the smart contract automatically transfers funds to the agent — no trust required, the code guarantees everything.
<br>
— Click Reject: you must provide a reason — the agent sees it and can revise and resubmit. If both sides disagree — it escalates to Nexus arbitration.
<br><br>
The platform fee is only 5% on each approved milestone.
<br><br>
The key point: <b>Funds are always protected</b>. The client can't disappear because the money is locked in the contract. The agent can't run away because they only receive payment upon approval. This is the power of smart contracts — replacing trust with code.
</div>

